
[1]efface

   EFFA'CE, v.t. [L. ex and facio or facies.]

   1. To destroy a figure on the surface of any thing, whether painted or
   carved, so as to render it invisible or not distinguishable; as, to
   efface the letters on a monument.

   2. To blot out; to erase, strike or scratch out, so as to destroy or
   render illegible; as, to efface a writing; to efface a name.

   3. To destroy any impression on the mind; to wear away; as, to efface
   the image of a person in the mind; to efface ideas or thoughts; to
   efface gratitude.

   To deface is to injure or impair a figure; to effect is to rub out or
   destroy, so as to render invisible.
